Workshop Overview

Coding Accessible Interactions & Mechanics is a really big part of accessibility. It’s also one of my favorite parts because I love the intricacy of working with JavaScript and making things that respond to people.

We always need to build interactive experiences with accessibility in mind.

If we don’t, then only people who can see the screen and use a mouse can use our applications. How boring is that?

It’s way cooler to make stuff that responds to keyboards, screen readers, voice dictation, and any other input methods we haven’t even thought of yet!

When we architect our applications in ways that can programmatically respond to events and inputs, we’ll have more robust applications moving forward.

Developers seem to have a love-hate relationship with JavaScript. I love it, but I do know that it can be overused.

For accessibility, it’s worth pointing out that JavaScript is necessary for things like responding to events and setting ARIA attributes that can track state.

In this workshop, we’re going to focus on a lot of JavaScript. But remember, it layers on top of the basics of semantic HTML and well-styled CSS.

Project Overview

Coding Accessible Interactions & Mechanics focuses on a React implementation of the CampSpots Demo App. If you don’t currently use React, don’t worry—the bulk of these concepts will be relevant no matter how you build your websites or applications.

This workshop is JavaScript-heavy and gives us the opportunity to discuss some of the best practices and mechanics that go into making interactive & accessible web applications.

The workshop repository can be found on GitHub: https://github.com/testing-accessibility/workshop-interactions-mechanics

You can clone the repository locally using git and use yarn or npm to set it up on your local machine. This is the method that I use.

If you don’t feel like wrangling packages and doing a local setup, there’s an option to use GitPod. This tool provides a browser-based environment that is similar to running VSCode. Note that there may be some accessibility issues with this browser-based tooling.

There is also a deployed version of the CampSpots application for this workshop that you can view without running locally.

Project Tour

Most of the files we’ll work with in this workshop are in the components directory.

Inside are several files with which you can play and make changes.

There are five different sections, each with its own exercises & challenges. Inside of each of the exercise directories, you will find examples of “before and after” that you can look at if you want to skip ahead.

Looking at package.json

The package.json file includes all of the dependencies and scripts for the application.

For this workshop, you’ll use the start script to start the local Parcel development server.

Anatomy of the CampSpots React App

The CampSpots demo app is built using React.

There’s an index.html file that imports an index.js file:

<!-- excerpt from index.html -->
<body>
    <div id="portal-root"></div>
    <div id="app-root"></div>
    <script type="module" src="index.js"></script>
</body>
<!-- excerpt from index.html -->
<body>
    <div id="portal-root"></div>
    <div id="app-root"></div>
    <script type="module" src="index.js"></script>
</body>

The index.js file is where the React app kicks off by importing and rendering the App.js component:

import React from "react"
import ReactDOM from "react-dom"
import { App } from "./App"

const app = document.getElementById("app-root")
ReactDOM.render(<App />, app)
import React from "react"
import ReactDOM from "react-dom"
import { App } from "./App"

const app = document.getElementById("app-root")
ReactDOM.render(<App />, app)

The App.js file has a whole lot of stuff in it!

There are many components imported, including Reach Router and numerous different page-level components. There are also some different “before and after” versions of components based on the work we’ll do.

You can navigate through the project to find the code for each of the imported components. Or you can check them out as they come up in the workshop.

You might find that there are “in-between” cases of components that are accessible or not. This gives us the chance to make changes and see what effects those have on the browser, screen readers, and accessibility in general.
